AWKA – The National Directorate of Employment (NDE) has commenced training for 50 women on Tye and Dye as a source of economic empowerment. The training will last for five days. In an Address by the state coordinator of NDE in Anambra State, Mrs. Chika Ufelle said the programme was being introduced because economic empowerment of women is central to the women’s ability to overcome poverty, cope with shocks and improve their well being. -Advertisement- According to her, when women realize their economic goals, whether in growing a business, improving their homes or investing in training or education, they will be more resilient and able to provide for themselves and their families. ” So, the training strategy was tailored to ensure that women are not trapped in poverty.” She noted. She further said that the training in tye and dye confirmed with the programme of women employment branch of NDE which focused on increasing women’s skills, both vocational and entrepreneurial, increase their decision making power and access to economic resources. Ufelle reiterated that similar training is taking place in the the 36 states of the federation and promised that more training will come before the end of the year. She asked the trainees to take the exercise seriously reminding them that “the success of the economy is not measured by high-rise buildings in the cities but in the robustness of the economy.” POLL The Director General of NDE, Mallam Abubakar Nuhu Fikpo who was represented by Mrs. Augustina Chikala, Director NDE, said this was why the main thrust of the programmes of the Directorate is hinged on skills acquisition,  enterprise development and rural-based. The State Coordinator thanked the Director General of the NDE, Mallam Abubakar Nuhu Fikpo for approving the training and facilitating their take off across the country. She encouraged the women to complete their training for their future endeavours.